WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:04.499
Now, if you don't know what meta learning is, let me quickly introduce the term.

00:05.140 --> 00:09.869
So in meta learning, you assume you have some sort of a distribution of tasks ahead.

00:10.410 --> 00:11.592
So let's make some examples.

00:12.153 --> 00:22.933
For example, task one could be you get an image, you have a data set of images, and you want to classify them into cats or dogs.

00:24.314 --> 00:28.819
And you know, you have a little data set with labeled images and you can train, test, split that.

00:29.220 --> 00:30.401
And that's one task.

00:31.002 --> 00:43.216
Now task two is going to be, again, you have a small data set of different images, but let's just all make image examples here, but you want to locate the pedestrian.

00:43.356 --> 00:46.220
So you want to locate the human in the image.

00:46.960 --> 00:50.284
So where is the human, right?

00:50.605 --> 00:52.667
And the task three could be,

00:54.503 --> 01:09.323
Again, a small database of tasks as sorry of images and in each of the image you want to visually question answer you want to or let's say you want to point out

01:10.552 --> 01:14.598
All right, there is a ground, there is a tree, and there is a question about it.

01:14.979 --> 01:17.002
Yeah, let's take visual question answering, right?

01:17.263 --> 01:20.969
We wish, which give you yes or no questions, something like this.

01:23.593 --> 01:27.499
Now let's just say you have to segment, you have to segment that image.

01:28.020 --> 01:31.125
So down here would be ground, you have to segment the ground.

01:31.105 --> 01:34.812
Okay, so these are all image tasks, right?

01:34.832 --> 01:39.881
These are all perfectly fine independent tasks, each for each one you have a small data set.

01:40.442 --> 01:48.496
Now, sometimes these data sets are very, very small, such that you cannot really train a state of the art model on them.

01:49.157 --> 01:51.882
For example, if you have medical images,

01:51.862 --> 01:55.347
Oftentimes the labels of these are very hard to get.

01:55.427 --> 02:02.458
I mean, there's privacy concerns and then, you know, doctors have to look at it to produce the images costs money and so on.

02:03.399 --> 02:08.026
So it's not like you have a lot of images and you could profit from more images.

02:08.286 --> 02:13.654
So one method that people come up with is called transfer learning.

02:13.834 --> 02:18.261
So in transfer learning, you say, I have this giant database of images.

02:18.321 --> 02:21.025
Let's, let's, let's say this is image net, right?

02:21.005 --> 02:24.630
I have this giant database image net with labeled images.

02:25.031 --> 02:29.517
What I can do is I can use this to train a neural network.

02:30.779 --> 02:33.683
Let's this are the bunch of layers of neural network.

02:33.703 --> 02:39.992
And I can train the neural network on this big database and get parameters theta, right?

02:39.972 --> 02:42.897
These are the parameters of the neural network.

02:43.378 --> 02:47.825
And then I will basically adapt these parameters to each task individually.

02:48.206 --> 02:55.237
So in task one, sorry about that, I would then take these parameters as an input to the neural network.

02:55.277 --> 02:58.362
I would initialize the neural network with these parameters.

02:58.863 --> 03:05.013
And then I would use this training set in order to fine tune.

03:05.073 --> 03:06.756
This is what's called fine tuning.

03:06.736 --> 03:10.843
to the task specific parameters here, phi.

03:11.243 --> 03:13.788
So phi one, because it's task one.

03:14.168 --> 03:25.707
For task two, I would also take these as a starting point in order to train its neural network to fine tune it on this bounding box task.

03:25.687 --> 03:28.812
in order to obtain the parameters for task two.

03:29.093 --> 03:35.624
So you can see that there's a pre-training stage here to obtain good initial parameters.

03:36.245 --> 03:43.257
And then we adapt these initial parameters for each task separately in a fine tuning stage.

03:43.237 --> 03:45.180
So this is one way we can do it.

03:45.901 --> 03:49.245
Another way we can do it is called multitask learning.

03:49.826 --> 04:03.404
What we do in multitask learning is we say, well, see, probably an neural network that can segment the grounds is also pretty good at doing bounding boxes, like it'll use some of the same features.

04:03.825 --> 04:09.953
So can't we just kind of pull together these data sets into one bigger data set?

04:09.933 --> 04:17.064
And then train on, like if it's an image from task one, we'll train on the loss of task one.

04:17.444 --> 04:21.010
And if it's an image from task two, we'll train on the loss of task two and so on.

04:21.431 --> 04:24.415
But we'll sort of use the same neural network basis.

04:24.475 --> 04:27.820
We just have kind of different heads on top of them.

04:28.521 --> 04:36.193
And we'll basically, so this is called multitask learning, have one shared neural network with different outputs for the different tasks.

04:36.173 --> 04:44.441
And basically counting on the fact that you can sort of learn from one task what's useful in the other.

04:44.481 --> 05:01.118
Now, this is a good method to combine the tasks and to basically share data information, but it will also limit you because you now have to trade off between the tasks, like this neural network right here, this joint encoder.

05:01.098 --> 05:13.240
will never be able to, will never be able to fully gear to one task because it all also has to, you know, it has to perform for the other tasks as well.

05:13.640 --> 05:16.986
So you kind of limit yourself in your top out accuracy.

05:17.908 --> 05:19.731
Now, maybe the regularization effect is good.

05:20.217 --> 05:22.200
So these are two methods.

05:22.260 --> 05:28.190
The first is called transfer learning here on the left and the other is called multitask learning.

05:29.051 --> 05:32.777
Now, meta learning goes a different direction.

05:33.018 --> 05:40.470
Meta learning is like transfer learning, but it says, well, what if we don't have this giant data set right here?

05:40.450 --> 05:48.785
What if we find a way to learn these initial parameters, right?

05:48.805 --> 05:54.877
So what we'll do is we'll start out with a guess, a guess of good initial parameters.

05:55.478 --> 05:57.261
Let's call that theta zero.

05:57.241 --> 06:11.628
And now we have all of these three tasks take Theta0 and run their fine tuning to come up with their own parameters, starting at Theta0.

06:11.689 --> 06:15.997
So this is Phi1 started from Theta0.

06:16.117 --> 06:19.283
And we'll also give it to Task2 and to Task3.

06:19.263 --> 06:19.924
Right.

06:19.944 --> 06:32.506
And each of these tasks is going to train on its own training data set and then evaluate on its own validation data set and then report back a number.

06:33.748 --> 06:42.283
So we do this for every task and every task basically trains this runs through the validation data set reports back a generalization error.

06:42.263 --> 06:49.942
And then we know, once we get all the information from all the tasks, we know how good were these initial parameters, right?

06:49.962 --> 06:58.483
We get a measure of how easy is it for the tasks to adapt these initial parameters to their own data set.

07:00.033 --> 07:07.828
And then we somehow need to figure out a way, okay, these parameters were on average 81% good.

07:08.429 --> 07:14.420
Can we come up with a better set of initial parameters theta one in some way?

07:14.741 --> 07:23.357
Can we somehow find a better set of initial parameters such that it is easier for the tasks to adapt these initial parameters, right?

07:23.337 --> 07:31.718
And even more so, there could be task four, which we are not seeing during this training phase, right?

07:31.758 --> 07:36.550
This is kind of our, so these up here could be our train training tasks.

07:36.771 --> 07:39.658
And this down here could be our validation task.

07:39.638 --> 07:56.858
So basically, we're trying to come up with a set of initial parameters that if a new task comes along and it takes this thing as its initial parameters, it will be able to adapt very quickly these initial parameters to its own data set.

07:57.439 --> 07:59.922
And most importantly, it can do that.

08:00.462 --> 08:08.852
It will result in a much better model than had the task just trained on its own small data set from scratch.

08:08.832 --> 08:20.424
So our task is in meta learning is basically to come up with a learning procedure to generate to iteratively generate better and better and better initial parameters, right?

08:20.444 --> 08:24.495
And what better way to do this than using gradient descent?

08:24.475 --> 08:34.134
So, this is meta-learning using gradient descent is the core of this paper, basically.

08:35.737 --> 08:37.400
Now, what do you need for gradient descent?

08:37.480 --> 08:46.297
So, if you want to go from one task to the next using SGD or even GD, gradient descent, you need to come up with a gradient.

08:46.638 --> 08:50.044
Now, why is this a problem in this case?

